John Harrington reviewed ''Big Bang'' for ''[[Games International]]'' magazine, and gave it 3 stars out of 5, and stated that "If I had to sum up ''Big Bang'' in just one sentence I would describe it as stimulating, educational but not addictive."<ref name="gi11">{{cite journal | last = Harrington |first = John | title =Computer Games | journal = [[Games International]] | issue = 11 | pages =50â€“51 |date=December 1989}}</ref>

''[[The Games Machine]]'' praised the game booklet and felt that players would feel a "wide range of emotions" as their companies gain and lose value.<ref name="TGM">{{Cite web|url=https://archive.org/details/thegamesmachine-12/page/n61/mode/2up|title = The Games Machine Magazine Issue 12|date = November 1988}}</ref>

Rod Lawton for ''[[ACE (magazine)|ACE]]'' complimented the game, saying "if you've got any entrepreneurial blood in you at all you'll be hooked".<ref name="ACE">{{Cite web|url=https://archive.org/details/Ace_Magazine_Issue_14/page/62/mode/2up|title=Ace Magazine Issue 14}}</ref>

Rob Murray from ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'' commended the graphic display, and felt that "Much thought has gone into the program".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/97934750/the-daily-telegraph/|title = Clipped from the Daily Telegraph|newspaper = The Daily Telegraph|date = 23 October 1989|page = 29}}</ref>

''[[PC Leisure]]'' called ''Big Bang'' "[...] initially compelling, but ultimately pointless, exercise."<ref name="pcleisure">{{cite magazine |last1=Sumpter |first1=Garth |title=Simulation - Big Bang |journal=[[PC Leisure]] |date=1990 |issue=1 |page=81 |url=https://archive.org/details/pc-leisure-01/page/n79/mode/2up |publisher=[[EMAP]]}}</ref>

